<HL>
   International:
   U.S., Britain
   Want to Defer
   Aid to Soviets
   ---
   Some Russian Economists,
   Leaders Agree That Plan
   Wouldn't Be Effective
   ----
   By Elisabeth Rubinfien
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- When Western leaders meet in Houston next week,
the U.S. and Britain plan to argue that a controversial plan
for massive aid to the Soviet Union is premature.
Surprisingly, leading Soviet economists and officials agree.
   West Germany and France have proposed an immediate $15
billion infusion of international aid, while Britain and the
U.S. say cash won't do any good unless serious economic
reforms are in place. Soviet economists say that the help
would be welcome, but that the country simply isn't ready to
absorb it yet.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I'm not sure such aid today would be effective," says
Oleg Bogomolov, an influential radical economist. "It won't
solve any of the cardinal problems."
   Even Soviet government officials reject the quick fix of
using Western funds to fill empty Soviet shelves. "All the
money in the world probably won't be enough to speed up
economic reform if we only do it through consumer goods,"
says Andrei Bugrov, a Foreign Ministry official specializing
in international economic relations.
   Before any aid could be effective, some Western and Soviet
experts argue, the country must start price reforms,
industrial privatization, reconstructing its banking system
and building better supports for foreign investment. Linking
the aid to such economic conditions could actually help
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev push through unpopular
reforms.
   But political conditions would be out of the question,
Soviet officials say. And many countries that are considering
participating in the aid plan clearly have their own
political agendas.
   West Germany, which initiated the idea, wants Soviet
acceptance of German reunification. The U.S. says it might
not participate unless the Soviet Union stops funding Cuba
and cuts its own military spending. Japan, now the world's
biggest creditor, won't give economic aid until it and Moscow
resolve their dispute over four islands north of Japan that
the Soviet Union has held since 1945.
   "Any intention to call the Soviet Union on the carpet in
Houston and dictate political conditions is extremely
unrealistic," wrote Lev Strzhizhovsky in Pravda, the
Communist Party daily. "There can be only one approach and
everyone in Houston should know it: `yes' to assistance, but
`no' to political conditions."
   The aid package is likely to dominate discussions at the
Houston meeting of seven major industrial nations. The G-7
summit participants -- the U.S., Japan, West Germany, France,
Britain, Italy and Canada -- are split on whether giving aid
is a good idea at all, and if so, how to go about it.
   The goal of France and West Germany is to help Moscow
through a difficult transition from 70 years of command
economy to a supply-and-demand market system. As a statement
of support for Mr. Gorbachev and his perestroika policies,
the aid plan emerged at the right time, just before the
crucial congress of the Communist Party that is now under way
and which could determine whether perestroika continues or
stalls.
   Last year, the G-7 countries called on the Soviets to
undertake specific economic reforms. Since then, several
reforms have been proferred and rejected, and the Soviet
economy has spiraled downward. Inflation is estimated at 10%,
the budget deficit last year hit 100 billion rubles ($170
billion at the official exchange rate or $16 billion at the
more realistic tourist rate), and hard currency debt now
stands at about $45 billion.
   When West Germany first suggested the aid plan last month,
it clearly wanted to give Mr. Gorbachev quick relief until a
more acceptable reform program could get off the ground. Some
of the money was proposed for food and consumer goods, to get
products on the shelves immediately.
   On its own late last year, the Gorbachev government
imported about 10 billion rubles of soap, food and clothing
in an attempt to soothe the tempers of striking miners and
frustrated city shoppers. At first the shipments did the
trick, but within a month the shelves were bare again and
nothing fundamental had changed.
   Many Soviet economists say that's the reason aid should be
linked to specific economic reforms or sorely needed
infrastructure such as roads and telecommunications. The
money must be earmarked for specific investments to avoid the
problems that plagued Poland in the 1970s, when tens of
billions of dollars of foreign investment and loans were
wasted, leaving the country with a huge foreign debt and lots
of outmoded equipment.
   Frustrated by the government's cautious approach to
reform, other Soviet economists say attaching economic
conditions to the aid could be just the lever needed to get
things moving. Without such external pressure, the stumbling
blocks in the way of economic reform will take too long to
remove.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Hidden Dangers in Species Extinction
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Michael D. Copeland's June 7 editorial-page article, "No
Red Squirrels? Mother Nature May Be Better Off," says that
the use by environmentalists of the Endangered Species Act
"is often a subterfuge for achieving other goals, such as the
prevention of development."
   Subterfuge, as I understand it, implies dishonesty at
worst, evasion at best. It doesn't fit. We use the Endangered
Species Act -- along with the National Environmental Policy
Act, the Clean Water Act, the Clean Air Act and scores of
other laws -- to achieve environmental protection.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Copeland attacked my colleague Andy Stahl for
acknowledging that the spotted owl was a useful ally in the
campaign to save a little of the pitiful remnant of
old-growth forest that still stands in the Pacific Northwest.
"Evidently, Mr. Stahl is more concerned with old-growth
timber than with the spotted owl," wrote Mr. Copeland, as if
that were a crime. Of course our goal is to protect old
growth: You can't have spotted owls without it. No one has
ever denied, to my knowledge, that we are in favor of
preserving old growth.
   Mr. Copeland exhibits considerable bravery in advocating
the extinction of species we know very little about. Bravery?
Make that arrogance. Historic extinctions caused by nature
are not necessarily equivalent to extinctions caused by man.
The latter reflect decidedly unnatural upsets and imbalances
in natural systems that we perpetuate at our peril.
   Tom Turner
   Staff Writer
   Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund Inc.
   San Francisco
   ---
   Using Mr. Copeland's logic, it could be argued that the
world would be better off without giant pandas, California
condors, the American bald eagle and developmentally disabled
people. Just who is to decide what species (or class) should
be sacrificed?
   Perhaps he should note that the past extinction of species
as a natural byproduct of evolution was not generally
something that happened overnight as a result of some
developer's whim or greed.
   Krisanne Edgcomb
   Lynden, Wash.
   ---
   I take exception to Mr. Copeland's contention that many of
the world's species are irrelevant since they stand in the
way of development projects.
   He makes two specious arguments. The first is that natural
mass extinctions, such as that of the dinosaurs, permit the
human race to extinguish more species or certain subspecies.
I assert on moral grounds that the human race has no such
right. Mr. Copeland's second argument is that biological
diversity, such as the existence of subspecies within one
species, is of no value. That argument is in serious error,
as demonstrated by the medical-research value of certain
species to humans as well as the interdependence of various
species within certain ecological systems. In certain cases,
the loss of one species can cause the collapse of an entire
system.
   In conclusion, I agree that development decisions should
not be totally blocked due to ecological considerations.
However, such development must clearly carry the burden of
proof that species extinction would not be the result. A
mountaintop observatory is not worth the extinction of any
species.
   James H. Maitland
   Darien, Conn.
   ---
   In response to Mr. Copeland's squirrel bashing and
greed-motivated rationalizations on the future of endangered
species, he quotes Harvard Prof. Stephen Gould on his
assessments of mass extinctions through time, stating that
today's species represent less than 1% of all species that
have ever existed. Extinctions of species through time were
caused by natural forces, before man ever walked on this
earth. Man is omnipotent when it comes to survival. He can
easily wipe out anything of his choosing. If we allow bending
of the rules of the Endangered Species Act, when would it
stop? We should be doing all we can to save that 1%.
   Donna Jean North
   Dallas
   ---
   Mr. Copeland's critique relies on arguments that belittle
the benefits of "individual animal or plant categories." We
can test the persuasiveness of those arguments if we
substitute the phrase "individual humans or class of humans"
for "individual animal or plant categories" and if we imagine
Mr. Copeland is not disputing the wisdom of this law, but
rather the wisdom of laws against murder and genocide.
   His assertions could then be paraphrased as follows: (1)
More than 95% of all humans who have ever lived are now dead;
(2) despite these many deaths, the human population is
actually increasing, past deaths making room for present
numbers; (3) nature obviously entails death as well as life,
so we may be wasting time, effort and money on humans who
will die over time regardless of our efforts; (4) human
traits that have helped folks survive in the past are not
particularly important to future longevity, so preserving
lives will not necessarily increase the life span of folks to
come.
   All these statements may be true. They are not necessarily
meaningful, however. They fail regarding human exterminations
for the same two reasons Mr. Copeland's arguments fail
regarding animal extinctions. First, he implicitly assumes
that teleological benefit-cost ethics are the only ones
relevant to decision-making in this case. Such ethics serve
nonmoral ends such as consumer welfare. He ignores imperative
ethics that find rightness or wrongness intrinsic to deeds
themselves, e.g., "Thou shalt not kill."
   Mr. Copeland could defend himself by saying that
imperative ethics should be ignored when it comes to keeping
people alive; that we should, for example, calculate the
benefits before spending added costs of, say $300 billion a
year on more medical care for the expiring elderly; and that
imperative ethics should likewise be ignored for species
preservation. This would be a good answer for Mr. Copeland if
by "species preservation" he meant efforts to keep alive
species that would die naturally from causes unrelated to
mankind's actions, just as it is a good argument when
considering health care for hopelessly ill humans. But we are
not talking about "species preservation" in this sense, which
brings us to the second flaw.
   The Endangered Species Act attempts to outlaw
exterminations of species insofar as they are caused by human
overharvesting or habitat destruction. People may find
imperative ethics useful here -- even imperative. Such ethics
are useful in assessing the genocide of the Tasmanian
Aborigines and our laws against the painful slaughter of
animals, not to mention more obvious matters. Similarly, the
Endangered Species Act reflects our attempt to apply
imperative ethics to the way we treat other species, not the
way Mother Nature treats them.
   These distinctions are critical. If Mr. Copeland could
convince us that the conscious taking of life forever lies on
the same moral plane as letting it expire naturally, then
teleological ethics might overrule imperative ethics, and his
arguments depreciating the benefits of individual species
might be meaningful.
   Douglas F. Greer
   Professor of Economics
   San Jose State University
   San Jose, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Subscribers' Lawsuit
   Against Cablevision
   Dismissed by Judge
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3A
</SO>
<CO>
   CVC PCI
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. -- A state court judge dismissed a
class-action lawsuit filed by Cablevision Systems Corp.
subscribers, charging the cable-TV operator with fraud,
restraint of trade and false advertising.
   The suit stemmed from a dispute between Cablevision and
the Madison Square Garden Network sports cable channel. MSG
is a subsidiary of Paramount Communications Inc.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In September 1988, a contract under which Cablevision
carried the MSG network as an optional service expired. MSG
had wanted Cablevision to carry the sports network as part of
a basic package. From mid-September until July 5, 1989, the
network wasn't carried on Cablevision at all.
   The subscribers charged that Cablevision was obligated to
reduce its rates while it didn't carry MSG, and they demanded
damages from the company.
   In dismissing the suit June 29, Judge John Copertino said
that when Cablevision started carrying MSG, the Woodbury,
N.Y., cable operator couldn't have known that the network
would become unavailable. Further, the court said, once the
dispute arose, Cablevision notified its subscribers that MSG
might become unavailable, and "all a dissatisfied customer
had to do was cancel the more-expensive package or terminate
the relationship in its entirety."
   On the issue of restraint of trade, the subscribers failed
to show a conspiracy existed to keep MSG out of Cablevision's
offerings, the court said. Cablevision also runs
SportsChannel, a sports network that competes with MSG.
   And the subscribers didn't show that at the time they
subscribed, "MSG was unavailable and that the advertising
complained of was then being run, rendering such advertising
or inducements to take service based on MSG's availability
`deceptive,'" the court said.
   Cablevision and MSG settled their dispute in July 1989; in
most of Cablevision's systems, MSG remained optional. It will
be an option on all Cablevision systems after the 1990
baseball season.
   Cablevision did reach agreements with state regulators to
make refunds to some subscribers. In November 1989, it agreed
to refund $490,545 to Connecticut subscribers; and in January
1990, it agreed to refunds in New York totaling as much as
$1.1 million. The company wasn't found to have violated any
laws or regulations.
   Thomas J. Sinnickson, the subscribers' attorney in Center
Moriches, N.Y., said the plaintiffs will seek to reargue the
case "based on new evidence arising from certain admissions"
Cablevision made in its settlement agreement in New York. The
plaintiffs also will file an appeal with a higher state
court, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0098
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0098.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Inside Track:
   Five Officials
   Of Gaming Firm
   Cash in Chips
   ----
   By Alexandra Peers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   PLAY NOVX CP HRB
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Five insiders at Players International Inc.
sold $2.5 million of the company's stock less than two weeks
before the share price plunged abruptly last month, filings
with the Securities and Exchange Commission show.
   The gambling-services company's chairman, president, vice
chairman, a director and vice president of marketing sold
405,300 shares May 31 and June 1, according to the filings.
The stock, which represented between 5% and 20% of their
holdings, fetched an average of $6.12 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   On June 13, the New York Daily News reported that Rep.
Bart Gordon (D.,Tenn.) was calling for a federal
investigation of the telephone-games business, which Players
had entered earlier in the month with a version of the
"Jeopardy" TV game show. According to the report, Rep. Gordon
said phone games might constitute gambling.
   Players stock, which had risen to a 52-week high of $8.50
a share after the company began test-marketing the game June
4, fell 28% in the two days following the report. It closed
yesterday in over-the-counter trading at $5.25, off 25 cents.
   Players Vice Chairman David Fishman, who sold 86,400
shares, said that the insiders sold their shares before
starting "Jeopardy" so that "no one could question our
intentions." As for the later stock drop, he asks, "How would
we know it was going to happen?"
   Four of the insiders at the Calabasas, Calif., company
also filed with the SEC on May 31 their intention to sell
more than a million additional shares "as soon as possible."
But Mr. Fishman said the filings were made in error, and that
there aren't any plans to sell any more stock.
   A spokesman for Rep. Gordon said the congressman wrote to
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh requesting an investigation
and that, late last week, the attorney general's office
responded that the matter has been referred to the Federal
Bureau of Investigation.
   Players' Mr. Fishman said its telephone "Jeopardy" game
"is well within the {Federal Communications Commission}
guidelines of not being gambling" because of the way it is
structured, and because it involves skill, not chance.
   To play the "Jeopardy" game, contestants call a 900-number
and answer 11 increasingly more difficult questions by
spelling out the first two letters of the answer on a
Touch-Tone phone. The game costs about $1 per minute to play
and offers a monthly grand prize of $10,000; there are also
smaller daily prizes.
   The game is a new business for Players International. The
company gets most of its revenue from its Players Club, which
offers members discounts on casino hotel rooms, meals and
shows.
   ---
   CAPITOL GAINS: Former President Gerald R. Ford sold a
third of his holdings in Nova Pharmaceutical Corp. last
month, SEC filings show. Mr. Ford, who serves as a director
of the Baltimore-based drug-research concern, received
$20,650, or $4.13 a share, for the 5,000 shares.
   Mr. Ford said he sold the stock "purely, totally for
income-tax-paying purposes." The former president said he
acquired the Nova shares through the exercise of options at a
price above the stock's current share price, creating "a
tax-loss benefit" upon their sale. He said he can use that
benefit to offset capital gains earned so far this year in
other transactions.
   "I'm keeping 10,000 {Nova} shares because I have great
faith in the company," Mr. Ford added.
   Separately, SEC filings also show that Nova
Pharmaceutical's president, Hans Mueller, bought 1,500 of its
shares on the open market, at an average price of $3.94 a
share, May 24 and May 25. The purchases increased his total
holdings 4%. He was in Europe and couldn't be reached for
comment.
   In over-the-counter trading yesterday, Nova closed at
$4.125, off 12.5 cents.
   ---
   CANADIAN MILLIONAIRE: In the largest insider sale reported
to the SEC last week, Michael G. Degroote, a director of
Canadian Pacific Ltd., sold 134.3 million Canadian dollars
(US$115.6 million) of its stock on June 21. He received C$22
(US$18.93) a share, the filings show. Canadian Pacific is a
Montreal-based holding company for a variety of
transportation, oil and gas, forestry and real estate
businesses.
   Mr. Degroote, who is chairman and chief executive officer
of another Canadian concern, Laidlaw Inc., sold 6,104,167 of
the shares he held indirectly in Canadian Pacific and kept
2,000 shares, according to SEC filings. Mr. Degroote acquired
the shares in 1988 when he sold a controlling interest in
Laidlaw to Canadian Pacific. He couldn't be reached for
comment.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Canadian Pacific
shares closed yesterday at $17.75, up 25 cents.
   ---
   SMALL CHANGE: Henry W. Bloch, chairman of H &amp; R Block
Inc., received $3 million for just 2% of his stake in the
Kansas City, Mo.-based tax-preparation and business-services
company. He sold 76,000 shares at an average price of $39.53
a share in sales June 21 and June 22, SEC filings show. Mr.
Bloch declined to comment.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, H &amp; R Block shares
finished at $41.50, off 87.5 cents.
   ---
   Georgette Jasen contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
