<HL>
   Citicorp Pushes Plan to Sell
   Insurance in Delaware
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Citicorp, responding to insurance industry
efforts to prevent it from using a Delaware subsidiary to
sell insurance, told the Federal Reserve that there aren't
any legal grounds to prohibit it from taking advantage of a
recently enacted Delaware law.
   Since the passage of the legislation giving
state-chartered banks insurance powers, Citicorp has been
preparing to underwrite and sell insurance through its
state-chartered unit, Citibank Delaware.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a memo to the Fed, the nation's largest banking company
said federal banking regulations allow state-chartered
subsidiaries of banks to engage in any activities in which
state-chartered banks themselves can engage.
   The insurance industry has argued that the Delaware law
permits banks to circumvent federal regulations that prohibit
banks from selling and underwriting insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
