900706-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Long List of Opponents
   To Telescope Project
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   In your May 23 Mount Graham editorial "A Species of
Extremism" you said, "no one has shown persuasively that the
project would harm the squirrel." For the record: All state,
federal and University of Arizona biologists who prepared the
official biological documentation have opposed it. Fish and
Wildlife Service biologists, under oath, testified against
it. Scientists nationwide have signed petitions opposing it.
University of Arizona biologists risked tenure and signed.
Max Planck and Ohio State scientists oppose their own
institutions' participation.
   You also stated: "Telescope backers promise to reforest
the logged areas." For the record, government biologists say
it takes 200 years to create the old-growth forest the
squirrel requires. It should be noted that only the
University of Arizona would be allowed to cut trees in
"critical habitat," having obtained congressional exemption
from all our environmental laws. Do you suggest we spend
millions of taxpayer dollars on a captive-breeding program so
the astronomers can destroy the squirrels' homes and food
supply?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   You said the project requires 26 acres, but that is only
the project "footprint." The government says the project
would destroy some 130 acres of squirrel habitat -- mostly
within the mountaintop's ecologically priceless 600-acre
virgin spruce-fir forest.
   What you did not say is that there are other places (New
Mexico, Nevada, Utah, Arizona, South America, etc.) for
advanced design telescopes that do not destroy endangered
species or irreplaceable ecological treasures. Studies have
ruled Hawaii's Mauna Kea far superior. Mount Graham was
listed in a recent study as 37th worst of 58 sites in the
Western U.S. Is a Univerity of Arizona astronomer's driving
convenience reason to trash our environmental laws?
   Jobs lost is pure hokum. There are institutions dying to
steal the University of Arizona's collaborators. Jobs follow
the collaborators.
   Regarding your disavowal of subspecies that "are found
elsewhere, have many subspecies or can be relocated" -- by
that definition you demean human races, preclude plant
varieties for lifesaving drugs and miracle grains, and ensure
a barren North America without grizzly bear, Florida panther
or Key deer since all the above are subspecies.
   Robert Witzeman, M.D.
   Conservation Chairperson
   Maricopa Audubon Society
   Phoenix, Ariz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Davis, Citicorp
   Corporate Finance
   Head, Steps Down
   ----
   By Robert Guenther
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Citicorp's head of North American corporate
finance, George L. Davis, resigned in what appears to be the
first fallout from a shuffling of top officers in January.
   Mr. Davis, 55 years old, couldn't be reached for comment.
However, a memo from Chairman John S. Reed to policy
committee members said that "the business has changed
considerably from that envisioned in 1987," when Mr. Davis
rejoined the large banking company. Mr. Reed's memo added,
"George feels that he can make a greater contribution
elsewhere."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Davis had left Citicorp in 1981 to become executive
vice president at First Chicago Corp. under Chairman Barry
Sullivan.
   Mr. Davis's resignation, Citicorp executives said, isn't
related to the bank's rising levels of problem loans for
corporate takeovers and commercial real estate, two troubled
areas that Mr. Davis oversaw.
   Rather, a bank executive who asked not to be identified
linked the departure of Mr. Davis, who is noted for his
credit analysis skills, to a political setback suffered by
Vice Chairman Lawrence Small, his patron within Citicorp.
   The January reorganization diminished Mr. Small's
influence within Citicorp and, some executives said, hastened
Mr. Davis's departure. In that shake-up, the traditional
commercial and investment banking functions were merged, and
the resulting wholesale bank split into two groups -- one
managing the developed countries, consisting of North
America, Japan and Europe; and the other managing the
developing countries.
   As part of that shake-up, Mr. Small, who had run the
world-wide commercial bank, was placed in a lesser role as
the top liaison with corporate clients, and Richard S.
Braddock, head of consumer banking, was elevated to the
long-vacant presidency.
   Mr. Small, a hard-charging, ambitious executive, was
considered by some the leading contender for the president's
job. However, Citicorp executives said disagreements grew
between Messrs. Reed and Small, especially over the tough
bargaining stance advocated by Mr. Small toward debt
negotiations with Brazil and other Latin American borrowers.
   At the time of the reorganization, Mr. Reed and other
Citicorp executives -- as well as Mr. Small himself --
insisted Mr. Small hadn't lost out. "With the age difference
of only two years between John and myself, I've never thought
that it was particularly logical for me to aspire to be chief
executive officer," Mr. Small said at the time.
   Michael A. Callen, who had been sector executive for
investment banking, was put in charge of wholesale banking in
the developed countries. Citicorp executives speculated that
Mr. Callen wants to fill key posts, such as Mr. Davis's
position, with personnel loyal to him.
   Mr. Callen was traveling yesterday and couldn't be
reached.
</TEXT>
