<HL>
   Coal Mining Firm,
   Dairy Face Fines
   On Safety Charges
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR T.LBT
</CO>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department proposed fines of
$508,000 against Pyro Mining Co., a coal-mining concern, and
$1 million against Johanna Farms, a dairy and citrus-product
packaging firm, on charges of safety violations.
   The department's Mine Safety and Health Administration
cited Pyro Mining's William Station mine in Union County,
Ky., for 121 violations, including alleged electrical-safety
violations and failure to make required safety examinations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The mine-safety agency said the proposed fine stemmed from
a methane explosion at the mine last September that killed 10
people. The agency said the explosion occurred after
explosive methane gas accumulated without being detected.
   The penalties would be a record amount for the mine-safety
agency, four times the largest fine assessed for any previous
single mine accident. The violations were "flagrant" and
showed Pyro Mining's "negligence," William Tattersall,
assistant secretary of labor for the agency, said.
   Separately, the department's Occupational Safety and
Health Administration cited Johanna Farms, Flemington, N.J.,
for violating safety and record-keeping standards. The
company, which packages dairy products, citrus juices and
yogurt, is a unit of John LaBatt Ltd., a holding company
based in North London, Ontario.
   Johanna Farms was cited for 197 willful instances of
failure to report injuries and illnesses and for 23 instances
of allowing workers to be exposed to unguarded machinery.
OSHA said 34 employees also were exposed to unguarded
sprockets and chains, among other safety violations. Gerard
Scannell, assistant secretary of labor for OSHA, said the
company suffered "a serious breakdown in its internal safety
and health program."
   Pyro Mining has 30 days to contest its citations and
proposed fine before the independent Federal Mine Safety and
Health Review Commission. Johanna Farms has 15 days to
contest its citations and fine before the Occupational Safety
and Health Review Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0069
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0069.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Greyhound Lines Agrees
   On Rent, Lease Payments
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   G X.GRE
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Greyhound Lines Inc., which filed for protection
under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy code last month,
said it agreed to resume paying its former parent company,
Greyhound Dial Corp., for rentals and leases on 15 major bus
terminals, a New York City maintenance facility and about
2,000 buses.
   Phoenix, Ariz.-based Greyhound Dial officials estimated
the payments at about $3.8 million a month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   J. Michael Doyle, Greyhound Lines senior vice president
and chief financial officer, said the agreement would permit
Greyhound Lines to develop its reorganization plan without
having to spend time deciding whether to assume or reject
hundreds of leases held by Greyhound Dial, which retains a
22.5% stake in the closely held bus company.
   Greyhound Lines and five other units of GLI Holding Co.
filed for bankruptcy law protection last month in
Brownsville, Texas, following a financially devastating
strike by the Amalgamated Transit Union.
   Although the agreement was filed with the U.S. Bankruptcy
Court in Brownsville, federal Judge Richard S. Schmidt was
not asked to approve it, although he has permitted Greyhound
Lines to use current revenue to meet operating expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0068
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0068.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Mr. Nader Goes to Moscow
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   Ralph Nader has just returned from a look at the new
Soviet man and is more than a bit discomfited at the shape of
things to come. While he did establish links with a new
consumer federation there, the latest Village Voice reports
he was "bewildered" by the fascination with free-market
ideology he found. "It's creeping anarchy," he told the
Voice. "Here is a system that was once ruled in an iron
grasp, and it's just falling out of control. . . . They're
swinging from Marx to Milton Friedman. They are the world's
experts on bureaucracy and the state. But they don't know
anything about what the market is going to do to them."
   Perhaps not, but it's our impression that the Soviet
citizenry has a crystal-clear view of what the public
bureaucracy has done to them. We called Mr. Nader for
amplification, and he outlined his nightmare of what a future
Soviet Union may look like.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A drive toward capitalism "means they will jump from the
frying pan into the fire. They are in danger of joining the
Third World and becoming an imitative economy and an
imitative culture borrowing everything from the West. They
are going from criticizing all that's Western to being
sycophantic about everything Western."
   Mr. Nader says many Soviets are only too willing to "sell
out" and become tools of multinationals poised to flood the
Soviet Union with useless products. "They don't need
Coca-Cola," he says. "They need nutritious fruit juices." He
warns that the Soviet Union is about to become a dumping
ground for the worst aspects of Western culture and
commercialism.
   Some of his Soviet hosts seem to have taken Naderism with
a grain of salt. Mr. Nader told Leningrad's Mayor Anatoli
Sobchak, an ardent free-market advocate, that democracy can
be perverted by powerful private interests. The Voice reports
that Mr. Sobchak gently told Mr. Nader that "our problems are
at a different level" and that "the key task is to wean power
away from the state and invest it in society. We must worry
about private power, but the immediate task is reducing the
power of the state over the economy."
   Mr. Nader was also startled when told by Moscow's reform
leaders that they wanted to create independent television
networks with foreign help. "I told them that even capitalist
America doesn't allow foreign ownership of television
properties," he says. "If they do that Western companies will
simply flood them with mindless American-style
entertainment."
   That's a thought worth pondering. Dumping segments of
"L.A. Law" on the Soviet Union might turn the whole reform
movement away from the U.S. system. Still, Sergei
Stankevitch, Moscow's deputy mayor, reminded him it was
impossible for them to create new networks without foreign
investment. "Why not try to combine leisure entertainment and
serious problems?" he asked Mr. Nader.
   Mr. Nader says he is still hopeful the Soviets can be
rescued from a headlong rush into the free market. He hopes a
nationwide consumer movement will act as a braking mechanism.
One possibility, we suppose, would be to rehabilitate former
KGB officials as Nader's Raiders or the Soviet Public
Interest Research Group.
   Of course, if Mr. Nader really wants to slow the pace of
change, he could just parachute in a few hundred U.S.
trial-lawyer friends. Once the American plaintiffs' attorneys
started suing the socks off the fledgling private sector,
that would guarantee that the Soviet Union would remain
uncorrupted by Western capitalism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Ratings:
   MNC Financial Gets
   Lower S&amp;P Ratings
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   MNC
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it lowered its
ratings on MNC Financial Inc. securities of about $2.1
billion, including a preferred stock issue that S&amp;P gave a
rating below investment grade.
   The rating agency lowered its rating on the preferred
stock to double-B-plus from triple-B-plus. Ratings on senior
debt were lowered to triple-B from single-A-minus and on
subordinated debt to triple-B-minus from triple-B-plus.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Also lowered to triple-B-plus/A-2 from single-A/A-1 were
ratings on certificates of deposit and letter of
credit-backed issues by units Maryland National Bank,
American Security Bank and MBNA America.
   Ratings for commercial paper of MNC Financial and unit
American Security Corp. were affirmed at A-2.
   S&amp;P said the downgrades reflect "continued weakness in
MNC's real estate markets and its significant concentration
in construction and commercial real estate loans."
   A spokesman at MNC, a financial services company based in
Baltimore, declined to comment.
</TEXT>
