<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Is Lower on Earnings Outlook;
   Transportation Index Is Poor Performer
   ----
   By Craig S. Smith
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Unlisted stock prices fell further in a market shaken by
more weak second-quarter earnings outlooks.
   Weakening expectations rattled the OTC market Monday and
Tuesday, and more pessimistic projections disturbed investors
yesterday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "They're definitely putting the jitters into the market,"
says David Memmott, OTC trader at Dillon, Read &amp; Co. Mr.
Memmott says OTC investor enthusiasm could be damped further
by a few disappointments early in the second-quarter
reporting period that will begin later this month.
   Many players stayed home yesterday, leaving some OTC
trading desks thinly staffed in anticipation of light
activity for the remainder of the week. The absences were
evident in volume, which totaled a mere 97.8 million shares,
compared to Tuesday's 131 million shares.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index dropped 2.57, or 0.56%, to
459.19, but suffered less than the New York Stock Exchange
Composite Index, which fell about 1.1%.
   Robert O'Toole Sr., head of institutional sales trading at
Shearson Lehman Hutton, says "buyers were on strike"
yesterday.
   OTC advancers trailed decliners, 676 to 1,094.
   Late Tuesday, Microcom slashed its previously reported
fiscal fourth-quarter and year-end results and said it also
expects to report a bigger loss for the first quarter than
had originally been anticipated.
   The company's stock lost nearly half of its value in June
after the company announced that it would lose money in the
first quarter ended June 30. The stock dropped nearly 30%
yesterday, down 2 5/8 to 6 1/8.
   On Tuesday, Mentor Graphics startled owners of its shares
by announcing that its second quarter profit would amount to
a mere 10 cents a share or less, far below expectations and
down sharply from the 29 cents a share reported in the
quarter a year ago. The company's stock suffered a 4 3/8
point loss Tuesday and fell another 7/8 to 16 3/4 yesterday.
   Specialty retailer Sharper Image slipped 3/8 to 4 7/8
after announcing that it expects to report a second-quarter
loss of 15 cents to 20 cents a share, compared with last
year's second-quarter profit of one cent a share. The company
blamed "the current retail environment" for the loss.
   Roadway Services fell 1/2 to 34 1/2. The trucking company
reported this morning that profit in the second-quarter fell
to 58 cents a share from 67 cents in the same quarter a year
earlier. The latest quarter's earnings were below analysts'
estimates.
   Other OTC transportation stocks slipped, including trucker
Yellow Freight Systems, off 1/4 to 26 7/8, and school-bus
operator Laidlaw, whose Class B shares eased 3/8 to 23 1/8.
The Nasdaq Transportation Index was the worst performing
sector of the OTC market, dropping nearly 0.9%.
   Hibernia Savings Bank lost 1 1/4 to 5 3/4 after omitting
its quarterly dividend. On Tuesday, the bank said it will
report losses for its second quarter and six months due to
real estate loan-loss provisions.
   Workstation makers Tandon and Sun Microsystems both edged
higher. Tandon gained 1/16 to 3 13/16 on heavy volume, while
Sun Microsystems gained 1/8 to 33 1/4.
   Apple Computer, however, fell 1/2 to 43 1/2, while
chip-maker Intel lost 1/2 to 47.
   Foremost fell another 3 3/8 to 22 1/4. On Tuesday, the
stock dropped 4 1/2 after the insurer said it had ended
efforts to find a buyer for the company.
   Hamilton Oil added 4 1/2 to 39 3/4 after it announced the
discovery of natural gas in the Irish Sea off the West coast
of England.
   Altos Computer gained 7/8 to 8 1/4 after signing an
agreement to be acquired by Acer Group for $8.35 a share.
   NEC's American Depositary Receipts rose 1 1/2 to 66. The
Japanese company has unveiled a mainframe computer that it
calls the world's fastest. However, analysts are skeptical
that the new machine will boost the company's tiny share of
the world mainframe market, according to an article that
appeared in this newspaper yesterday.
   CCAIR, which does business as USAir Express, said it filed
a petition for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
Bankruptcy Code. The stock lost 7/8 to 1 1/4.
   Insurance brokers firm Poe &amp; Associates added 3/4 to 12,
while fellow brokers Hilb, Rogal &amp; Hamilton rose 1/4 to 14.
Yesterday's "Heard on the Street" column in this newspaper
reported that some analysts are saying now is the time to buy
insurance brokerage stocks. Those analysts say the pricing
cycle for property and casualty insurance has bottomed and
may be ready for an upswing. Poe and Hilb, Rogal were two
firms cited as good buys by an analyst quoted in the story.
   Specialty soap maker Neutrogena added 1 3/8 to 23 1/8. At
least one analyst attributed the move to "short covering," in
which investors who have sold borrowed shares of the stock
buy new shares to repay their stock loans, according to Dow
Jones Professional Investor Report. Socalled short sellers
hope to gain from a drop in the price of a stock, and cover
their loans when they believe a stock's price has hit bottom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0055
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0055.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law:
   Eight Companies
   Are Named in Case
   On Toxic Labeling
   ----
   By Ken Wells
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   DOW S SBP
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Two environmental groups here said they
filed an administrative complaint against Dow Chemical Co.,
Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. and six other concerns charging that 16
common household spot removers and paint strippers made by
the companies violate California's tough toxic labeling law.
   Among the products named were Dow Chemical's popular K2-r
Spot-lifter and Sears Paint and Varnish Remover. Under the
law, makers of products containing known carcinogens must
label them with "a clear warning of the cancer risks."
Companies that fail to do so can face fines of as much as
$2,500 per consumer estimated to have bought the product
during the time that chemicals have been on the state's
official carcinogen roster.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the case of the 16 products named in the complaint, the
exposure is 15 months, thus the potential liability adds up
"comfortably to hundreds of millions of dollars," said David
Roe of the Environmental Defense Fund. The fund filed the
action with the Sierra Club. The toxics law, known as
Proposition 65, was adopted by voters in 1986 but contained
phase-in provisions designed to give companies time to
comply.
   The fund and the Sierra Club filed a similar complaint in
September against Gillette Co. for its alleged failure to
label its Liquid Paper correction fluid. Gillette, without
admitting guilt, agreed to pay a $300,000 settlement to the
state and changed the Liquid Paper formula to eliminate the
offending carcinogen.
   Under the toxics law, any citizen or group may file an
administrative action if it believes the labeling law isn't
being adhered to. The complaint by the fund and Sierra Club
triggers a 60-day period in which the state must decide
whether it will prosecute the alleged offenses. If it
declines to do so, the law allows the environmental groups to
file their own suits to seek damages on behalf of the public.
   As the Gillette case demonstrated, the unofficial purpose
of the 60-day period is to give alleged offenders an
incentive, avoiding the prospect of enormous fines, to
reformulate their products or quickly comply with Proposition
65's labeling provisions. Any such voluntary agreement,
however, "doesn't {necessarily} exempt the companies from
potential penalties," said the fund's Mr. Roe.
   Besides Dow Chemical, Midland, Mich., and Chicago-based
Sears, the action names Jasco Chemicals Corp., Mountain View,
Calif.; Standard Brands Paint Co., Torrance, Calif.; Thompson
&amp; Formby Inc., Montvale, N.J.; Carbona Products, Brooklyn,
N.Y.; Northern Labs Inc., Manitowoc, Wis.; and Cadillac Shoe
Products Inc. of Royal Oak, Mich.
   A Dow Chemical spokesman said, "If we're not in
compliance, we'll change that. But whether or not we're in
compliance, I can't say right now." He added that there has
been some confusion over which products should be covered by
the law.
   Daniel Thomas, general manager of Jasco, and Craig Walker,
a Standard Brands vice president, said the companies hadn't
seen the complaint but are in compliance with the law.
   Officials of the other companies couldn't be reached for
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0054
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0054.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- On Sports:
   Will Lendl Win It at Last?
   ----
   By Frederick C. Klein
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<LP>
   London I think I should begin this piece by saying that I
like Ivan Lendl, the tennis player. He is punctual and
polite, and able to make small jokes in a language not his
own (English), no small feat. I interviewed him once, and he
invited me to his home, showed me around and offered me a
Diet Coke. That may be no more than expected in most circles,
but in jockdom it passes for high hospitality.
   He is conscious of the history of his sport and concerned
about his place in it, other attributes that many top
athletes do not share. Further, he does not pretend to
disdain what he has not been able to obtain, another minority
position among the accomplished.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As anyone who can follow the bouncing ball knows, what
Lendl hasn't been able to obtain is a Wimbledon singles
title, which would round out a rare career "Grand Slam." How
much he wants one has been a main topic of discussion at
these proceedings, which enter the men's semifinal round
today with him still in it.
   The bony-faced Ivan and the assembled press have spent the
fortnight fencing about the meaning of the word "obsessed."
The former Czech lad, now a 30-year-old Connecticut squire,
won't accept that psychologically loaded label, but has said
he would trade all of his previous Grand Slam crowns,
numbering eight (three French, three U.S. and two Australian
Opens), for the All-England bauble. That might not amount to
obsession, but the price Faust paid wasn't much higher.
   Lendl has gone about his quest in his characteristic way,
which is to work very hard at it; this is a guy who, if he's
not playing tennis, is running, bicycling, pumping iron or
engaging in some other athletically useful activity. He and
his coach, Tony Roche, have noticed that Wimbledon is played
on grass, and have shaped their spring schedules around
spending as much time as possible on the surface. This
entailed skipping the claybound French Open, where Ivan is
very much at home, and at which he would have been the
favorite.
   It's here appropriate to note that finding a grass tennis
court is no easy matter. The things are difficult and
expensive to maintain, yield bad bounces in the best of times
and wear down easily; by the time this tournament is over,
Wimbledon's famed and pampered Centre Court will be as much
brown as green, and sport wellworn ruts along its back and
center lines.
   I have played tennis for 25-odd (really odd) years, and
have never set foot on a grass court. Neither, I'd guess,
have you. There are some here in England, of course, and a
scattering in Australia and the U.S., mostly at clubs that
also have "cricket" or "croquet" in their names. The surface
is, in a word, archaic, which is why it's silly to call
Wimbledon the world's tennis championship, as some do. But
that's another subject.
   If any of the above indicates that Lendl has been a
failure in this tournament over the years, it's
unintentional. He's reached the finals twice -- in 1986 and
1987 -- and last year led Boris Becker, the eventual
champion, two sets to one in a semifinal before bowing. He
thus reasoned that a little improvement would go a long way,
and that greater grass-court familiarity would provide it.
   Asked the other day what he's worked on, he mentioned his
footwork and return of serve, and, naturally, his volleying,
the last of which dispenses with erratic grass-court bounces.
But he added: "Mostly it's just spending the time on grass;
not having to pack all my preparation into a few days. This
year, if it rained, we could do something else and not worry
that we were losing time we couldn't make up."
   It could be that Ivan is right, but it also could be that
he's wrong, and that longer lawn time won't help him. My view
is that the ability to play successful grass-court tennis is
a knack, like juggling or being able to memorize whole pages
of a telephone book at a glance. Players of all styles and
nationalities have won here, some with little or no
background on the stuff.
   Sweden, for example, has about as many grass courts as it
has Club Meds, but its Bjorn Borg won Wimbledon five times,
and he was a bred-in-the-bone base liner to boot. Germany has
a similar lack, but in 1985 a 17-year-old Becker showed up in
the men's draw for the first time, said the German equivalent
of "aw, shucks," and whupped everybody country-style. He's
done it twice more since, without special preparations, and
is back in the semis again today.
   It could be that Lendl secretly shares my view, because he
has shown little pleasure in his labors here to date. He
dropped a set in his first-round match with Christian
Miniussi (ranked 116th), another in round three to Bryan
Shelton (No. 125), another in the fourth round to Alex
Antonitsch (48), and yet another in Wednesday's quarterfinal
with Brad Pearce (120), a chunky Utahan whose main previous
distinction was that he'd made the doubles final in a
tournament in Schenectady.
   Poor Ivan has grouched around more than usual, and
continually taps his shoes with his racket between points.
That latter gesture perhaps expresses a wish to be back home
on clay, where shoe-tapping serves a purpose (to knock out
the dirt).
   After his match with Shelton, a pleasant but limited young
player from Huntsville, Ala., Lendl explained how the
wham-bam of grass-court tennis offended his methodical
nature. He noted that while Shelton's forehand was lacking,
"you can't expose his weakness on grass. His serve is big,
and every now and then you get a funny hop on the serve, and
then he comes in and hits some decent volleys." So instead of
something like 6-3, 6-2, 6-1, the scores were 7-6, 6-7, 6-4,
6-4, and "whew."
   It's true that Lendl has been aggressive here, looking,
for a change, a bit more comfortable at the net than a hooked
salmon. It's also true that after beating the Austrian
Antonitsch on Tuesday he declared, "I'll never stay back
again," meaning that he wouldn't revert to his base-lining
ways.
   But he quickly smiled and said he was kidding, which
looked truest of all. If he does win here, Wimbledon just
might never see him again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900706-0053
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900706-0053.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   Dollar Gains as Traders Seek to Correct
   Oversold Positions Ahead of Jobs Report
   ----
   By Thomas L. Waite
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST CANDA JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The dollar strengthened against other major
currencies yesterday as dealers moved to correct, and profit
from, what many considered an excessive recent decline by the
U.S. currency.
   Many U.S. foreign exchange dealers took the day off,
apparently stretching Wednesday's Independence Day holiday
into a long weekend. Those who were active here and in other
markets around the world seemed to be concentrating on
establishing positions ahead of today's June U.S. employment
report.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "A lot of traders came in looking for a lower dollar"
after the currency's retreat in Asian and European trading
Wednesday, said Thomas Palladino, a New York assistant vice
president for Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank.
   "There seemed to be an incentive to push the dollar
lower," Mr. Palladino said, but the move didn't get the
support it needed. "Finally people decided {to say} to heck
with it, square up and wait for employment to come out."
   Michael McGuinness, a foreign currency investment officer
with Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank in Chicago, attributed the
lack of strong selling to a "feeling that most things have
been overdone" on the dollar's downside, especially what he
called the currency's "skyrocketing decline" against the
British pound.
   "The market was oversold," said Manfred Totzauer, senior
trader for Citibank in Frankfurt, explaining the dollar's
rise in European trading yesterday. If the U.S. report today
on non-farm payroll growth is much better than expected, he
said, "short-covering could take us two pfennigs higher"
against the mark.
   Although the dollar stood higher in late New York trading
yesterday than it was a day earlier in London, it was only
mixed by comparison with its pre-holiday New York levels. The
dollar was quoted at 1.6517 marks, up from 1.6505 late
Tuesday in New York and from 1.6467 marks late Wednesday in
London. The U.S. currency was also changing hands at 150.60
yen, which was down from 150.90 in New York before the
holiday but up from 149.75 in London late Wednesday.
   Sterling was trading at $1.7815, up from $1.7775 in New
York Tuesday but down from $1.7845 in London Wednesday.
   In Tokyo early Friday, the dollar was trading at 151 yen
soon after the opening, unchanged from Thursday's Tokyo
close. Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was trading at 1.6553
marks, up a bit from Thursday's Tokyo close of 1.6551 marks.
   The employment report, due for release at the start of the
New York trading day, will contain the first official U.S.
economic data for June. Market anticipation of easier U.S.
credit has grown in recent weeks. Currency dealers will
scrutinize the data for signs of a U.S. slowdown because they
assume that Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
will do the same.
   Non-farm payrolls are believed to have grown by 83,000 in
June, or by 132,000 if layoffs of temporary census workers
are excluded, according to the average of estimates of 20
economists.
   This would follow a gain of 164,000 in May, which included
the hiring of about 145,000 temporary census workers.
   Notwithstanding the market's recent run of thin,
directionless sessions, today "is going to be a wild day,"
said Brian Jones, an economist with Salomon Brothers in New
York. "You're going to get hit with a barrage of numbers," he
said. "Unless they're all going in one direction, you're
going to get bounced around until people have digested the
information."
   Mr. Jones said the often-overlooked hourly wage component
of the employment data may give the Fed a signal on interest
rates that contradicts the one contained in the employment
data. Analysts look for an average gain in hourly earnings of
0.3%, compared with a 0.4% gain in May.
   The dollar finished higher in Tokyo trading Thursday.
Japanese dealers suggested that the market had sold the
dollar too short Wednesday and observed that life insurance
companies entered the market Thursday, buying the dollar
around 150 yen. Other participants followed, but the dollar
subsided after it failed to break resistance about 151 yen.
   A report in the Financial Times newspaper that Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev had been warned by a group of
"prominent politicians, scientists and army officers" of a
possible military coup also helped the dollar gain against
the mark in Tokyo, traders said.
   The most active cross, or non-dollar, trading was between
the pound and the mark. Long, or overbought, pound positions
were unwound against the German currency after the pound
reached about 2.95 marks in early European trading. Sterling
ended the New York session at 2.9425 marks, compared with
2.9385 marks late Wednesday in London.
   London traders still expect sterling to test an area
between 2.98 and 3.00 marks. They also see a chance for the
pound to move toward $1.80 in the next few weeks on
speculation about Britain's possible full entry into the
European Monetary System.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current
delivery settled at $361.40 an ounce, down 70 cents.
Estimated volume was a light two million ounces.
   In early Hong Kong trading Friday, gold was quoted at
$360.60 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
